  "texts": [
    "However, this approach tends to result in high false-positive rates as it overlooks the inherent complexity of a sample.",
    "For training the attack models [239], attacks of this type are based on a highly optimistic and arguably unrealistic assumption in many cases that an adversary knows the distribution of training data of the target model [307].",
    "Mattern et al.",
    "proposed a neighborhood attack that relies on the concept of using neighboring samples, generated through data augmentations like word replacements, as references for inferring membership, which aims to develop a metadata-free mechanism [161].",
    "Mireshghallah et al."
